(1009, 1, '2013-06-07 11:43:42', '2013-06-07 11:43:42', '<strong><a href=\"http://condovest.com/files/2013/01/Longwood-Image.png\" rel=\"shadowbox\"><img title=\"Longwood Image\" alt=\"Longwood Condominiums\" src=\"http://condovest.com/files/2013/01/Longwood-Image-300x193.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"193\" /></a>\r\nPopulation:</strong>13,732\r\n<strong>Demographics:</strong>Median age is 42; 85.5 percent white, 5.1 percent black, 15.8 percent Hispanic\r\n<strong>Median household income:</strong>$57,439\r\n<strong>Schools:</strong>Sabal Point Elementary School, Wekiva Elementary School, Woodlands Elementary School, Milwee Middle School, Rock Lake Middle School, Teague Middle School, Lyman High School, Lake Mary High School, Lake Brantley High School\r\n<strong>Entertainment:</strong>Several sites listed on the U.S. National Register of Historic Places, including the Victorian Bradlee-McIntyre House, the Longwood Hotel, and the Longwood Historic District, which has 37 historic buildings.\r\n\r\n<strong>Need Help Renting, Buying or Selling A Condominium in Longwood, FL.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Call Us Today! 407-477-2546</strong>\r\n\r\nLongwood made national news early in 2012 for all the wrong reasons. The Senator, a 3,500-year-old pond cypress tree  the oldest of its kind in the world  was destroyed when a drug addict started a fire at the base of the tree, killing Floridas oldest tourist attraction that had been a great part of the states history since Native American tribes used it as a landmark to help guide them to their trading grounds.\r\n\r\nThe Senator, named after Florida State Senator Moses Overstreet, was nearly 120 feet tall and had been dedicated with a bronze plaque in 1929 by President Calvin Coolidge. It was recognized as the fifth oldest tree in the world. Fortunately, it is survived by another tree of the same species known as Lady Liberty in Longwoods Big Tree Park. Lady Liberty is only 89 feet high and estimated to be 2000 years old; another one of the oldest trees in the world.\r\n\r\nDespite the senseless loss of The Senator, Longwood is a lovely wooded area in Seminole County, northeast of Orlando with enough stands of tall trees to justify the citys name, even though the moniker was actually borrowed from a suburb of Boston by one of the areas earliest American settlers. Meanwhile, the word Seminole, used to designate the county, is a combination of Spanish and Creek (Native American) terms for people who live away from others; and the area was indeed an early settlement for various Indian tribes from the Eastern United States who became known as the Seminole Indians.\r\n\r\nThe earliest American settlers began coming to Longwood in the time period between the end of the Seminole Wars and the beginning of the Civil War. However, it was when Edward Warren Henck, a railroad pioneer, brought his family there in 1873 that the area became established with a post office and hotel. Henck became the citys first mayor in 1885 governing the city of 1,000 people; and a decade later, the burgeoning city had three hotels, five churches, eight stores and a weekly newspaper. Not surprisingly given the areas many trees, it soon became home to the P.A. Demens &amp; Co. the major supplier of lumber and building materials for much of the area.\r\n\r\nRailroad expansion in Florida and the Central Florida citrus industry added to Longwoods growth and economy until a devastating freeze in 1894 caused people to flee the area, leaving Longwoods population at just 325 by the census of 1900. For about the next 50 years, Longwood went through periods of rebound and decline. It was incorporated as a city in 1923, but didnt experience real growth until the nearby Kennedy Space Center and Walt Disney World brought economic stability in the 1960s and 1970s. Today, Longwoods population exceeds 13,700 people\r\n\r\nBecause it is almost equidistant from Orange Countys major tourist attractions, a major job source, as it is from the East Coast beaches of Florida, Longwood is popular both as a place to live and to visit, especially for golfers. There are at least 10 different golf courses within 15 miles of Longwood.\r\n\r\nThere is no denying the historical significance of Longwood. As a result, the city has taken steps in recent years to revitalize its downtown historic district. The city has also grown through annexation.\r\n\r\nThere are a number of notable sites worth visiting in Longwood, including the Bradlee-McIntyre House, the Longwood Hotel and the surviving oldest pond cypress, Lady Liberty.', 'Longwood', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '856-revision-7', '', '', '2013-06-07 11:43:42', '2013-06-07 11:43:42', '', 856, 'http://bricrealty.com/856-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1010, 1, '2013-06-07 11:28:41', '2013-06-07 11:28:41', '<a class=\"ether-frame ether-frame-1 alignright\" rel=\"shadowbox\" href=\"http://condovest.com/files/2013/01/Maitland-IMage.png\">\r\n<img width=\"300\" height=\"179\" src=\"http://condovest.com/files/2013/01/Maitland-IMage-300x179.png\" alt=\"Maitland Condominiums\" title=\"Maitland IMage\" style=\"border: 1px solid black;margin: 1px 2px\">\r\n</a>\r\n<strong>Population:</strong>15,751\r\n<strong>Demographics:</strong>Median age is 41.3; 80.59 percent white, 11.06 percent black, 10.42 percent Hispanic\r\n<strong>Median household income:</strong>$66,453\r\n<strong>Schools:</strong>Dommerich Elementary School, Lake Sybelia Elementary School, Hungerford Elementary\r\nSchool, Maitland Middle School, La Amistad School, Summit Charter School: private schools are\r\nPark Maitland School, Lake Forrest Preparatory School, Hebrew Day School, Maitland Montessori\r\nSchool, Center for Early Childhood Education, King of Kings Lutheran School, Chabad Day School and\r\nOrangewood Christian School\r\n<strong>Entertainment:</strong>Enzian Theater, Florida Film Festival, Maitland Art Center, Maitland Civic Center (musical\r\nand special events) La\r\n\r\n<strong>Need Help Renting, Buying or Selling A Condominium in Maitland, FL.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Call Us Today! 407-477-2546</strong>\r\n\r\nAlthough it is only about six square miles in size, the Orlando suburb of Maitland has so many lakes 18\r\npercent of the area is water, making it a haven for boaters. The largest body of water, Lake Maitland,\r\nis the defining geographical feature and the area was named after a fort that was built on the western\r\nshore of the lake (then called Fumecheliga) in 1838. The U.S. Army established the fortress in honor of\r\nCapt. William Seton Maitland, a hero of the Seminole Wars, and the name stuck even after the fort had\r\nbeen torn down.\r\n\r\nThe citys main thoroughfare was once part of the Old Black Bear Trail, which ran from Montreal,\r\nCanada, to St. Petersburg, Florida, and passed by the fort. After the Civil War, Maitland continued to\r\nbe a popular spot for Northern guests to winter because of the mild climate, fresh spring water and\r\npine forests. Before long, a healthy citrus industry began to sprout. Soon a railroad connection was\r\nestablished to Jacksonville and a large packing house in the center of town shipped as many as 300,000\r\nboxes of fruit each season. The city also was home to an ice factory, two livery stables and had a hotel,\r\nPark House, which became a resort for such luminaries as presidents Grover Cleveland and Chester\r\nArthur.\r\n\r\nMuch of Maitlands growth in the 20th century can be attributed to Americas quest for dominance in\r\nspace. Located less than 50 miles from Cape Canaveral, Greater Orlando attracted the Martin Marietta\r\nCorp. and many employees settled their families in Maitland due to its proximity to the plant. Like the\r\nrest of the Orlando area, Maitlands growth also benefited from the arrival of Walt Disney World in\r\n1971.\r\n\r\nToday, the population of Maitland is about 16,000 and consists primarily of residential neighborhoods\r\nwith a commercial sector of banking, retail, services and notably, Electronic Arts Tiburon studio, makers\r\nof the popular Madden NFL series and NCAA Football series. The city is served by two elementary\r\nschools and a middle school; high school students attend the nearby Winter Park High School. The\r\nInterlachen School of Dance is also in Maitland.\r\n\r\nFor a small town, one of the oldest incorporated suburban municipalities in Central Florida, Maitland\r\nhas remarkable number of cultural facilities. It is home to the Maitland Art Center, which is listed on the\r\nNational Register of Historic Places for its unique Mayan Revival and Fantasy Architecture, the Maitland\r\nHistorical Museum, the Telephone Museum, the William H. Waterhouse House Museum, and the\r\nCarpentry Shop Museum.\r\n\r\nBut perhaps drawing the most traffic annually is the Enzian Theater, one of the premier art house\r\ntheaters in the Southeast. It not only screens small-budget, first-run independent features and foreign\r\ntitles from the film-festival circuit, but also older films with a twice-monthly program it calls Cult\r\nClassics.\r\n\r\nThe theater is a not-for-profit organization dedicated to entertain, inspire, educate and connect the\r\ncommunity through film, according to its mission statement. Founded by Tina Tiedtke and the Tiedtke\r\nfamily in 1985, it has gained a loyal following of film lovers and garnered a national reputation with its\r\nwillingness to book self-distributed films. The Enzian hosts the renowned Florida Film Festival every\r\nspring, as well as the annual Central Florida Jewish Film Festival, the South Asian Film Festival and the\r\nBrouhaha Film &amp; Video Showcase, an exhibition of works by Florida film students.\r\n\r\nThe Enzians outdoor Eden Bar is a popular spot for drinks and a bite to eat, as are RanGetsu and the\r\nCopper Rocket Pub. Many restaurants are located nearby in Winter Park.\r\n\r\nDue to its rich history, Maitland has an active historical society and preservation program. An historical\r\ncorridor includes old residences still standing in the area of Lake Lily and Lake Catherine and extends\r\nthrough the central portion of the city. Examples include: the Arthur OHeir House (1885), Chadburne\r\nHall or High Oaks (1890), the James Arch House (1885), the Robert L. Wagner House (1881) and the Hill-\r\nStone House (1908).\r\n\r\nAmong famous residents who have called the city home are Buddy Morrow, leader of the Tommy\r\nDorsey Orchestra, and Scott Stapp front man of the rock group Creed.', 'Maitland', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '861-revision-5', '', '', '2013-06-07 11:28:41', '2013-06-07 11:28:41', '', 861, 'http://bricrealty.com/861-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
